Broadway, west side, north from West 24th, across 25th, to 26th Street's, showing respectively, the Hotel Albemarle at the N. W. corner of 24th Street; the double unit Hoffman House at the S. W. corner of 25th Street; and the Hotel St. James at the S. W. corner of 26th Street. To the right is Fifth Avenue, separated from Broadway by the Worth Monument.

About 1890

Gift of Urbrock Collection

Broadway, west side, from 24th to 26th Streets. At the left is the Albemarle Hotel; the building adjoining it and the corner building together constitute the Hoffman House. At the extreme right is the St. James Hotel, which will be the first of these three hotels to give way to an office building, a fate to which they are all doomed.

About 1890.

Brown Brothers.

Broadway, west side, from 24th to 26th Streets. At the extreme left is the Fifth Avenue Hotel. In the next block is the Hotel Albemarle, and the next two buildings constitute the Hoffman House, which has recently been remodelled and enlarged. On the S.W. corner of 26th Street, the St. James Building has replaced the St. James Hotel.

1899.

J. S. Johnston, from Brown Brothers.

Broadway, west side, from West 24th to 25th Street's, showing the hotels Albemarle and Hoffman House. The first is on the left, at the N. W. corner of 24th St. The Hoffman House is composed of the two taller buildings and is shown behind the Worth Monument. The middle building is the oldest, having been opened in 1864. It was replaced in 1885 by the present 8 story structure. In 1904 the Broadway side was rebuilt. The entire hotel was closed in 1914 and demolished in 1915.

About 1911

H. N. Tiemann, photo
Gift of Urbrock Collection

(1) Broadway, west side, north from 24th Street. The buildings in the left foreground, from 24th to 25th Streets, replaced the Albemarle Hotel and the Hoffman House.

About 1922.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection.

(2) The same showing also a part of the Fifth Avenue Building, which replaced the Fifth Avenue Hotel, in the right foreground.
